{{Infobox Chinese | pic = The Chinese Gold and Silver Exchange Society.jpg | piccap = Chinese Gold and Silver Exchange Society headquarters | t = 金銀業貿易場 | p = Jīnyínyè Màoyìchǎng | y = Gāmngàhnyihp Mauhyihkchèuhng }}
[[File:HK SW Lee Cheong Gold Wu Hon Fai Bonham Strand.JPG|thumb|right|Logo of CGSES member firm Lee Cheong Gold Dealers on their shop at [[Bonham Strand]], [[Sheung Wan]]]]
The '''Chinese Gold and Silver Exchange Society''' is an organisation of gold trading firms in [[Hong Kong]] who are participants of the Chinese Gold and Silver Exchange, the first [[exchange (organized market)|exchange]] in Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://capitalentrepreneur.com/common_emag/view_content.php?issue_no=53&pub_id=23&top_id=108&art_id=80663|title=香港金銀業貿易場 奠定香港金融地位|trans-title=Hong Kong's Gold and Silver Exchange Society: establishing Hong Kong's financial position as an Asian trading center|work=Capital Entrepreneur|issue=107|year=2009|accessdate=2013-11-10}}</ref>
==History== The CGSES was formally established as an organisation in 1910.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://paper.wenweipo.com/2010/11/17/zt1011170001.htm|title=走過百年 歲月流金|trans-title=Passing through 100 golden years|periodical=[[Wen Wei Po]]|date=2010-11-17|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=2677516|first=Catherine R.|last=Schenk|year=1995|title=The Hong Kong Gold Market and the Southeast Asian Gold Trade in the 1950s|periodical=Modern Asian Studies|volume=29|number=2|pages=387&ndash;402|doi=10.1017/S0026749X00012786}}</ref> Its founders were immigrants from mainland China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MFwxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8qQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5852,3972852&hl=en|title=Cheerful chaos is big business on Hong Kong gold market|work=Montreal Gazette|date=1981-08-29|accessdate=2013-11-10}}</ref> It eventually stopped trading silver, but gold trading saw significant growth after 1974 when the government loosened legal restrictions, and by 1979 trading volume was roughly one million ounces per day, making it one of the world's four largest gold trading centres along with [[London]], [[New York City]], and [[Zurich]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=w7MwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-PoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3894,947462&hl=en|title=Gold trading in Hong Kong wild, wooly|work=Associated Press|date=1979-08-17|accessdate=2013-11-10}}</ref>
==In politics== Members of the CGSES entitled to vote at its general meetings are one of two categories of persons eligible to register as [[Financial Services (constituency)|Financial Services functional constituency]] electors, the other being exchange participants of [[Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing]]. This gives them the right to elect a representative to the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]], as well seats in the [[Election Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reo.gov.hk/pdf/gn/fs_e.pdf|title=Guidance Notes: Application for Registration as an Elector in a Functional Constituency and as a Voter in an Election Committee Subsector: Financial Services|publisher=Registration and Election Office|location=Hong Kong|year=2012|accessdate=2013-11-10}}</ref>
