{{Infobox organization | name = Society for the Preservation of Downtown Los Angeles | native_name = | image = | image_size = 165px | alt = A black box with two keys and with "Society for the Preservation of Downtown Los Angeles" written inside | caption = | abbreviation = SP-DTLA | formation = 2015 | founder = | type = [[501(c)(3) organization|501(c)(3)]] [[nonprofit organization]] | status = | purpose = Supporting Sustainable Commercial and Residential Development in Historic Downtown Los Angeles | headquarters = [[Downtown Los Angeles]], California | location = | coords = <!--{{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}}--> | region = | services = | leader_title = Director | leader_name = Alex Hertzberg | website = [http://www.sp-dtla.org/ sp-dtla.org] | nickname = SP-DTLA }}
'''Society for the Preservation of Downtown Los Angeles''', also known as '''SP-DTLA''', is a [[501(c)(3) organization]] that advocates what it characterizes as responsible and respectful development around and among [[Downtown Los Angeles]]' historic structures. SP-DTLA supports development with a positive impact on the designated [[List of Los Angeles Historic-Cultural Monuments in Downtown Los Angeles|Los Angeles Historic-Cultural Monuments in Downtown Los Angeles]], especially those in the [[Historic Core, Los Angeles|Historic Core]].<ref>Curbed Los Angeles. [http://la.curbed.com/archives/2015/09/new_downtown_la_tower_would_block_views_of_historic_eastern_columbia_clock.php New Downtown LA Tower Would Block Views of Historic Eastern Columbia Clock]</ref><ref>Los Angeles Times. [http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-essential-california-html-20151002-htmlstory.html Saving the View]</ref>
SP-DTLA supports viewshed protection<ref>[http://www.preservationnation.org/information-center/law-and-policy/legal-resources/preservation-law-101/resources/Viewshed-Protection.pdf] National Trust for Historic Preservation - APPROACHES TO VIEWSHED PROTECTI0N AROUND THE COUNTRY</ref><ref>[https://data.seattle.gov/browse?tags=historic+register Seattle designated individual sites, buildings, vehicles, vessels, and street clocks as landmarks subject to protection by city ordinance]</ref><ref>[https://www.djc.com/news/re/11124625.html Protecting views makes sense from every angle]</ref><ref>[http://www.qcode.us/codes/sacramento/view.php?cite=section_17.216.860&confidence=6 Sacramento City Code 17.216.860 C-3 zone—Capitol view protection requirements]</ref><ref>[https://www.preservationaustin.org/advocacy/capitol-view-corridors/ Capitol View Corridors]</ref><ref>[http://www.fairfaxcounty.gov/dpz/historic/overlaydistricts.htm Historic Overlay Districts]</ref><ref>[http://www.fairfaxcounty.gov/dpz/historic/overlaydistrictsguidelines.htm Historic Overlay District Design Guidelines]</ref><ref>[http://www.nj.gov/dep/opsc/docs/hpo_princeton.pdf PRINCETON TOWNSHIP HISTORIC PRESERVATION ORDINANCE AND AMENDMENTS]</ref> and a "zone of respect" around preserved buildings.<ref>[http://www.preservationalliance.com/publications/SenseofPlace_final.pdf SENSE OF PLACE: DESIGN GUIDELINES FOR NEW CONSTRUCTION IN HISTORIC DISTRICTS] pg. 29</ref><ref>[http://articles.philly.com/1987-02-26/news/26179358_1_mayor-goode-city-hall-corridors A 'Zone Of Respect' For City Hall]</ref><ref>[https://www.ncpc.gov/heightstudy/docs/Case_Study_Research.pdf Height Master Plan For Washington, DC Case Study Research] pgs. 15 & 18</ref><ref>[http://preservation.lacity.org/ Los Angeles Office of Historic Resources]</ref><ref>[http://planning.lacounty.gov/preservation Los Angeles County Historic Preservation]</ref>
SP-DTLA's particular focus is on the seven by four block area (3rd to Olympic Streets and Hill to Main Streets), which includes the [[Broadway Theater District (Los Angeles)|Broadway Theater District]].
==Current Causes== [[File:LA Eastern Columbia Building.jpg|thumb|upright|LA Eastern Columbia Building]] SP-DTLA is best known for its opposition to the Alexan South Broadway project in proximity to the 1930 [[Eastern Columbia Building]] and its landmark clock.<ref>Alice Walton, [http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-essential-california-html-20151002-htmlstory.html "Newsletter"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', October 2, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://la.curbed.com/2015/9/30/9915574/new-downtown-la-tower-would-block-views-of-historic-eastern-columbia "New Downtown LA Tower Would Block Views of Historic Eastern Columbia Clock"], [[Curbed|Curbed Los Angeles]], September 30, 2015.</ref> The group is also opposing two other downtown projects which they argue have a height and mass out of scale with the character of the adjacent historic buildings.<ref>Hillel Aron, [http://www.laweekly.com/news/will-three-proposed-skyscrapers-harm-the-character-of-dtlas-historic-core-6981515 "Will Three Proposed Skyscrapers Harm the Character of DTLA's Historic Core?"], ''[[LA Weekly]]'', June 1, 2016.</ref>
