{{nihongo|'''William Hiroyuki Saito'''|齋藤ウィリアム浩幸||born March 23, 1971}}<ref name=FamilySearch-CABirthIndex-1971>{{cite web|title=William H Saito, California Birth Index, 1905-1995|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VGFX-YDW|website=[[FamilySearch]]|date=23 March 1971}}</ref><ref name=BBC2015>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-34122635|title=Teaching Japan to take more risks|last=Nguyen|first=Hoang|date=2015-09-14|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> is a [[Japanese Americans|Japanese American]] businessman, venture capitalist and former advisor to the [[government of Japan]] specializing in [[cybersecurity]].<ref name=BBC2015/> 

In December 2017 reports emerged on the Internet that he had falsified his education and work experience, and he resigned from his government and other advisory posts, apologized, and issued corrections.<ref name=JapanTimes2017>{{cite news|title=Former METI adviser Saito rewrites resume after quitting government posts under cloud of doubt|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/12/22/national/former-meti-adviser-saito-rewrites-resume-quitting-government-posts-cloud-doubt/#.WmeB1ainHIU|work=The Japan Times Online|date=22 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=":2" />

== Early life and education ==
Saito was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]; his parents immigrated to the US from Japan in 1969, two years before he was born.<ref name=UnprogrammedLife-2012>{{cite book|last1=Saito|first1=William Hiroyuki|title=An Unprogrammed Life: Adventures of an Incurable Entrepreneur|date=2012|publisher=Wiley|location=Singapore|isbn=978-1-118-07727-6|oclc=778431581}}</ref><ref name=BBC2015/> He is the eldest of three children.<ref name=BBC2015/>

In 1987, Saito graduated from [[Damien High School]] in [[La Verne, California]].<ref name=DamienHigh-Laconian-Keynote-2015>{{cite news|last1=Lin|first1=Justin|title=William Saito, Entrepreneur and Alumnus, to Speak at Damien Graduation|url=https://issuu.com/dhsspartans/docs/the_laconian_may_2015|work=The Laconian|volume=XLVII|issue=7|date=May 2015|pages=1-2|language=en}}</ref> He attended the [[University of California, Riverside]] from the Fall of 1988 to the Fall 1992,<ref name=TokyoReporter-Riverside-2018>{{cite news|title=University attended by William Saito says he did not graduate|url=https://www.tokyoreporter.com/2018/01/05/university-attended-by-william-h-saito-says-he-did-not-graduate/|work=[[Tokyo Reporter]]|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> and was a student in Riverside's joint Biomedical Science Program with the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1988.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=TokyoReporter-Riverside-2018 />

== Career ==
Saito began a computer security venture while in junior high school, and incorporated the firm as I/O Software in 1991 while attending university.<ref name=BBC2015/> Among other technologies, I/O Software developed a system to display [[Japanese writing system|Japanese characters]] in software written in English, and a [[fingerprint]] recognition system used by [[Sony]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1f92e6da-37b7-11e2-a97e-00144feabdc0|title=William H. Saito: Embrace failure to nurture entrepreneurs|last=Blair|first=Gavin|date=2012-12-03|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref> [[Microsoft]] began a partnership with I/O Software in 2000 to adopt the latter's authentication technology in future versions of [[Microsoft Windows]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.microsoft.com/2000/05/02/microsoft-and-io-software-strengthen-industry-adoption-of-biometrics/|title=Microsoft and I/O Software Strengthen Industry Adoption of Biometrics|last=|first=|date=2000-05-02|work=Microsoft|access-date=2018-01-25|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> Saito sold the I/O Software business assets to Microsoft in 2004.<ref name=BBC2015/><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /><!-- Relevant quote from Saito's blog: 私はこれまで、Microsoft社にI/O Software社を売却したと説明していましたが、正確な表現を心がけるならば、「事業全部の移転」と申し上げるべきかもしれません。 -->

After selling the I/O Software business, he moved to Japan, where he became active as a [[Venture capital|venture capitalist]] and invested in several Japanese start-ups.<ref name=BBC2015/><ref name=":3" /> He was named a [[Young Global Leader]] of the World Economic Forum in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www3.weforum.org/docs/WEF_YGL_Honourees_2011.pdf|title=List of 2011 Young Global Leaders Honourees|publisher=World Economic Forum|date=2011-04-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828142522/http://www3.weforum.org/docs/WEF_YGL_Honourees_2011.pdf|archivedate= 28 August 2011}}</ref>

Following the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]] in March 2011, Saito was appointed to provide IT and technical support to the [[National Diet]] committee investigating the disaster. He used the title of "Chief Technology Officer" in this role and later admitted that this title exaggerated his actual responsibilities.<ref name=":2" /><!-- Relevant quote: 私は、国会東京電力福島原子力発電所事故調査委員会にて、委員会で利用するPC等のインフラ構築、保守管理等の業務に携わっていました。そこでの私の立場は、調査そのものにはタッチしない、一般企業でいうところのいわゆる「システム部門」の担当者でした。その際、肩書をどのようにするべきか問われたため、「最高技術責任者（CTO：Chief Technology Officer）」を提案したところ、問題なく了承され、事務方から名刺をいただきました。 -->

Saito was at one time a top advisor to Prime Minister [[Shinzō Abe|Shinzo Abe]] on cybersecurity issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/japanrealtime/2015/07/01/top-abe-cybersecurity-adviser-says-japan-could-be-global-leader-in-field/|title=Top Abe Cybersecurity Adviser Says Japan Could Be Global Leader in Field|last=Mochizuki|first=Takashi|date=2015-07-01|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref> He was formally a cybersecurity advisor to the [[Cabinet Office (Japan)|Cabinet Office]] from 2013 to 2017, and an advisor to the [[Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry]] from 2016 to 2017.<ref name=JapanTimes2017/> He also served as a member of the technical task force for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] and [[2020 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]], and as an advisor on education policy to the [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology]].<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nikkan-gendai.com/articles/view/news/220162|title=経歴詐称の斎藤ウィリアム浩幸氏 なぜ自民党は重用したか|last=|first=|date=2017-12-24|website=Nikkan Gendai|language=ja|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> Saito accompanied Abe on a 2015 visit to [[Silicon Valley]], where Abe met with the heads of several major technology firms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/r-abe-seeking-new-spark-for-japan-high-tech-heads-to-silicon-valley-2015-4|title=Shinzo Abe wants to bring Silicon Valley to Japan|last=Layne|first=Nathan|date=2015-04-30|work=Business Insider|access-date=2018-01-29|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|agency=Reuters|last2=Wilson|first2=Thomas|language=en}}</ref>

In the private sector, Saito was appointed as a strategic advisor to [[Japan Airlines]] in 2015, and provided advice to JAL on its IT strategy. He served as a part-time Executive Officer and as the first General Manager of Digital Innovation Promotion at JAL from May to December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO17061060Q7A530C1000000/|title=JALが「デジタルイノベーション部」、起業家を招へい|last=金子寛人|first=|date=2017-05-30|work=[[The Nikkei]]|access-date=2018-01-25|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=ja-JP|quote=2015年4月からJALの戦略アドバイザーを務めており、IT関連の施策についてアドバイスをしていた。今回非常勤の執行役員として、より具体的にJALのIT活用に携わる。}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://press.jal.co.jp/en/items/uploads/22DEC%20Press%20Memo.pdf|title=JAL Announce Changes to Executive Officers/Assignment|last=|first=|date=2017-12-22|website=Japan Airlines|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref> He was a member of the advisory board of ''[[The Japan Times]]'' from 2014 to 2015,<ref name=JapanTimes2017/> and also served as an advisor to [[Hakuhodo]] and [[Fast Retailing]].<ref name=":5" />

In December 2017 the writer [[Ichiro Yamamoto (writer)|Ichiro Yamamoto]] raised questions on his blog about Saito's claims that he graduated from UCLA's medical school and about his work experience in cybersecurity.<ref name=JapanTimes2017/><ref>{{cite news|title=William Saito resigns as METI adviser amid questions about background |url=https://www.tokyoreporter.com/2017/12/22/william-h-saito-resigns-as-meti-adviser-amid-questions-about-background/|work=Tokyo Reporter|date=December 22, 2017}}</ref>

Saito resigned from his Cabinet and METI advisory positions in December 2017, citing personal reasons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tokyo-np.co.jp/article/economics/list/201712/CK2017122202000129.html|title=「サイバー対策専門家」　経産・内閣府参与辞任|last=|first=|date=2017-12-22|work=[[Tokyo Shimbun]]|access-date=2018-01-25|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=ja-JP}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASKDQ54FVKDQUTFK013.html|title=斎藤ウィリアム浩幸氏、内閣府などの参与辞任　経歴訂正：朝日新聞デジタル|last=|first=|date=2017-12-22|work=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|access-date=2018-01-25|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=ja-JP}}</ref> The same day, Japan Airlines announced that he had resigned as a digital innovations officer.<ref name=TRtwitter>{{cite news|title=William Saito denies NYT report on buying Twitter followers|url=https://www.tokyoreporter.com/2018/02/26/william-saito-denies-nyt-report-on-buying-twitter-followers/|work=Tokyo Reporter|date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> After leaving his posts, on his website he said that he did not graduate from UCLA medical school, and clarified his role in investigating the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster.<ref name=JapanTimes2017/><ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://saitohome.com/ja/6280-2/|title=ブログ等におけるご指摘について|last=Saito|first=William Hiroyuki|date=2017-12-21|work=saitohome.com|access-date=2018-01-24|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=ja}}</ref> <!-- Relevant quote from Saito's blog: このように、ITの世界に魅了され、追求する中で医師の道を中途で断念したというエピソードを披露することを繰り返すうちに、事実と異なる経歴を語ってしまったことは私の過ちでした。UCLAの医学部を卒業し、医師免許を取得したという事実はございません。 --><!-- Relevant quote: しかし、国会事故調という組織の任務を考えれば、「最高技術責任者」という肩書は、原子力技術に関する高度な知見を有して調査に関与している人物であるかのような誤解を受ける可能性があると思い至るべきでした。私の実際の職務に比して、このような肩書を用いることが適切といえたか、その後もかかる経歴を示すことが適切であったかと問われると、軽率であったと反省しています。 --> Following these revelations, economy minister [[Hiroshige Sekō]] stated that no falsifications had been found in the resume that Saito submitted to METI in connection with his hiring.<ref name=":4" />

In January 2018 an article in the ''[[New York Times]]'' listed Saito's twitter account as among those for which [[ghost followers]] had been purchased from Devumi.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Confessore|first1=Nicholas|title=The Follower Factory|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/01/27/technology/social-media-bots.html|work=The New York Times|date=2018}}</ref><ref name=TRtwitter/> Saito denied that he had done this, and deleted his Twitter account.<ref name=TRtwitter/>

